That is possible. In fact [I recommend this approach in an article I wrote&amp;nbsp;&lt;sup&gt;\[django-antipatterns\]&lt;/sup&gt;](https://www.django-antipatterns.com/antipattern/using-commit-false-when-altering-the-instance-in-a-modelform.html).

But I would advise to let the form handle the logic, like:

&lt;!-- language: python --&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;def dog_view(request):
    # &amp;hellip;
    form = DogForm(request.POST, request.FILES)
    if form.is_valid():
        form.instance.race = &#39;Labrador retriever&#39;
        &lt;b&gt;form.save()&lt;/b&gt;
    # &amp;hellip;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

The main reason for this is that Django forms also can save many-to-many fields, and thus make more database queries. By using `dog.save()` you save the dog instance, and in this case, that is fine. But if you have a `ManyToManyField` named `owners` for example. It will thus no longer save the owners of the dog.


---

&gt; **Note**: While most forms do not process media files, it is probably better to pass [**`request.FILES`**&amp;nbsp;&lt;sup&gt;\[Django-doc\]&lt;/sup&gt;](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/stable/ref/request-response/#django.http.HttpRequest.FILES) to the form anyway, such that if you later add an extra media field, all views that use the form will indeed handle the files properly.

