answer_md:
In `my_rust_function()`, take [`Bound&lt;&#39;_, PyAny&gt;`](https://docs.rs/pyo3/latest/pyo3/prelude/struct.Bound.html) (or any variant, such as [`Borrowed&lt;&#39;_, &#39;_, PyAny&gt;`](https://docs.rs/pyo3/latest/pyo3/prelude/struct.Borrowed.html) or [`Py&lt;PyAny&gt;`](https://docs.rs/pyo3/latest/pyo3/prelude/struct.Py.html), but prefer `Bound` unless you have reasons not to), and use the [`call0()`](https://docs.rs/pyo3/latest/pyo3/types/trait.PyAnyMethods.html#tymethod.call0) method on it to call it without arguments, or [`call1()`](https://docs.rs/pyo3/latest/pyo3/types/trait.PyAnyMethods.html#tymethod.call1) to call it with positional arguments only, or [`call()`](https://docs.rs/pyo3/latest/pyo3/types/trait.PyAnyMethods.html#tymethod.call) to call it with both positional and keyword arguments.

Exporting the Rust function to Python should be done as usual.

For example:

```rust
use pyo3::prelude::*;

#[pyfunction]
fn my_rust_function(a: usize, f: Bound&lt;&#39;_, PyAny&gt;) -&gt; PyResult&lt;usize&gt; {
    f.call1((a,))?.extract::&lt;usize&gt;()
}

#[pymodule]
fn rust_module(m: &amp;Bound&lt;&#39;_, PyModule&gt;) -&gt; PyResult&lt;()&gt; {
    m.add_function(wrap_pyfunction!(my_rust_function, m)?)?;
    Ok(())
}
```

