&gt; I found in internet that the best way to do this is to use `setattr()` function, so I made all and.

**No**. For &quot;ordinary&quot; classes that might work. But Django&#39;s `Model` has some advanced meta-logic, meaning attributes not passed when constructing the class, might end up not in the model.

What you need is to use the &lt;code&gt;.contribute_to_class(&amp;hellip;)&lt;/code&gt; method, like:

&lt;!-- language: python --&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;models.OneToOneField(
    Competition,
    default=&#39;for_nothoing&#39;,
    on_delete=models.RESTRICT,
    help_text=&#39;which competition is it taking part?&#39;,
)&lt;b&gt;.contribute_to_class(PlayerInstance, &#39;choice_to_competition&#39;)&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

**But**, you don&#39;t need to do this trick to refer to a model not yet created. Indeed, for a [**`ForeignKey`**&amp;nbsp;&lt;sup&gt;\[Django-doc\]&lt;/sup&gt;](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/stable/ref/models/fields/#django.db.models.ForeignKey), [**`OneToOneField`** *model* field&amp;nbsp;&lt;sup&gt;\[Django-doc\]&lt;/sup&gt;](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/stable/ref/models/fields/#django.db.models.OneToOneField) and [**`ManyToManyField`** *model* field&amp;nbsp;&lt;sup&gt;\[Django-doc\]&lt;/sup&gt;](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/stable/ref/models/fields/#django.db.models.ManyToManyField), you can use a string literal to refer to a model that has not yet been defined, with:

&lt;!-- language: python --&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;class PlayerInstance(models.Model):
    choice_to_competition = models.OneToOneField(
        &lt;b&gt;&#39;&lt;em&gt;app_name&lt;/em&gt;.Competition&#39;&lt;/b&gt;,
        default=&#39;for_nothoing&#39;,
        on_delete=models.RESTRICT,
        help_text=&#39;which competition is it taking part?&#39;,
    )
    # &amp;hellip;


class Competition(models.Model):
    # &amp;hellip;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

If the model has the same app label, you can even drop the *`app_label`*:

&lt;!-- language: python --&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;class PlayerInstance(models.Model):
    choice_to_competition = models.OneToOneField(
        &lt;b&gt;&#39;Competition&#39;&lt;/b&gt;,
        default=&#39;for_nothoing&#39;,
        on_delete=models.RESTRICT,
        help_text=&#39;which competition is it taking part?&#39;,
    )
    # &amp;hellip;


class Competition(models.Model):
    # &amp;hellip;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;


---

&gt; **Note**: Models normally have no `Instance` suffix. An object from a class is always called an &quot;*instance*&quot;, by naming the class &lt;code&gt;&amp;hellip;Instance&lt;/code&gt;, one gets the impression that the variable is an instance of a class.

